Analysis of Dataset B

2025-02-06

Dimension of the dataset

cat("The dataset has", nrow(HLA_discov_et_validation_431), "rows and", ncol(HLA_discov_et_validation_431), "columns.\n")
## The dataset has 431 rows and 23 columns.

Structure of the dataset

To highlight the variables:

str(HLA_discov_et_validation_431)

All the variables, divided by type

1. Demographic and Lifestyle Data

  • numIM: Identification of the patient no analysis
  • Age: Patients age in years
  • Sex: Patients sex
  • Smoking history: Patients smoking history
  • histology: Histologic type of the tumor

2. Disease Progression and Survival Data

  • os_status: Overall survival status of the patient
  • osduree: Overall survival duration
  • pfsduree_immunoth: Progression-Free Survival (PFS), duration without the progression of the tumor under immunotherapy

3. Immunotherapy Data

  • Immuno Line: Line of immunotherapy treatment received
  • nb_meta_beforeimmuno: Number of metastases detected before immunotherapy
  • ps_befimmuno: Performance Status before the treatment

4. Therapy Response

  • ipd_status: Indicates whether the patient developed immunotherapy-related disease progression
  • dcr: Disease control rate
  • iORR: Objective response rate

5. Biologic Parameters

  • LeucoTpre: Total white blood cell count before treatment
  • NeutTpre: Total neutrophil count before treatment
  • LDHpre: Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) levels before treatment
  • dNLR: Derived neutrophil-to-lymphocyte ratio
  • dNLR_categ: Classification of D-NLR into categories
  • dNLR_pre_lipi: ? no analysis
  • LDH_lipi: ? no analysis
  • LDH_categ: Classification of pre-treatment LDH levels
  • lipi_pre: Score of Lipi-Index, a score that combines LDH and dNLR

Pre-processing

To a better use of the dataset, a normalization of the names of the columns/variables is preferible

library(dplyr)
library(data.table)

HLA_discov_et_validation_431 <- HLA_discov_et_validation_431 %>%
 rename_with(~ tolower(.) %>%              #better using lowercase characters
                gsub(" ", "_", .) %>%      #better using underscores instead of whitespaces
                gsub("-", "_", .) %>%      #better removing special characters (-)
                gsub("\\(|\\)", "", .))    #better removing special characters (())

Statistic summary

summary(HLA_discov_et_validation_431)

Most Suitable Response Variable (Target)

  1. If the goal is to predict the progression of the disease:
    • ipd_status binary response
  2. If the goal is to estimate the time before the progression:
    • pfsduree_immunoth continuous variable
  3. If the goal is to predict patient survival:
    • os_status binary
  4. If the goal is to evaluate the clinical response: (both continuous variables)
    • dcr
    • iORR

Missing values

How many missing values are in the dataset?

Its important to check how many NAs values are in the dataset.

sum(is.na(HLA_discov_et_validation_431))
## [1] 89

How to handle the missing values?

Now, to understand what are the best suitable techniques to use to manage the NAs values, I check for each column (first) and for each row (after) the percentage of missing values

library(naniar)
vis_miss(HLA_discov_et_validation_431)

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
#FOR COLUMNS
gg_miss_var(HLA_discov_et_validation_431, show_pct = TRUE) +
  labs(title = "Percentage of missing values for variable") +
  theme_minimal()

missing_values <- colSums(is.na(HLA_discov_et_validation_431))


missing_percentage <- (missing_values / nrow(HLA_discov_et_validation_431)) * 100


missing_report <- data.frame(
  column = names(HLA_discov_et_validation_431),
  missing_values = missing_values,
  missing_percentage = missing_percentage
) %>%
  arrange(desc(missing_percentage))  

num_columns_above_40 <- sum(missing_report$missing_percentage > 40)
print(paste("Number of columns with missing percentage > 40%:", num_columns_above_40))
## [1] "Number of columns with missing percentage > 40%: 0"
#VERY CONSISTENT DATASET (the highest percentage (of missing values) is 7 %)

Since is useless, i eliminate it

col_useless <- c("numim")
HLA_discov_et_validation_431 <- HLA_discov_et_validation_431 %>%
  select(-all_of(col_useless))
# FOR ROWS
gg_miss_case(HLA_discov_et_validation_431) +
  labs(title = "Number of missing values for row") +
  theme_minimal()

missing_values <- rowSums(is.na(HLA_discov_et_validation_431))

missing_percentage <- (missing_values / ncol(HLA_discov_et_validation_431)) * 100

missing_report <- data.frame(
  row = 1:nrow(HLA_discov_et_validation_431),  
  missing_values = missing_values,
  missing_percentage = missing_percentage
) %>%
  arrange(desc(missing_percentage))  

num_rows_above_50 <- sum(missing_report$missing_percentage > 50)
print(paste("Number of rows with missing percentage > 50%:", num_rows_above_50))
## [1] "Number of rows with missing percentage > 50%: 0"
#AS FOR THE COLUMNS (the highest percentage is 17%)

Analysis of the numeric variables

is_binary_with_na <- function(x) {
  unique_vals <- unique(x[!is.na(x)])  
  all(unique_vals %in% c(0, 1))  
}
binary_cols <- colnames(HLA_discov_et_validation_431)[sapply(HLA_discov_et_validation_431, is_binary_with_na)]
num_var <- HLA_discov_et_validation_431[, sapply(HLA_discov_et_validation_431, is.numeric)]
num_var <- num_var[, !(colnames(num_var) %in% binary_cols)]

SMOKING HISTORY

HLA_discov_et_validation_431 <- HLA_discov_et_validation_431 %>%
  mutate(smoking_history = case_when(
    smoking_history == "CURRENT" ~ "current",
    smoking_history == "FORMER" ~ "former",
    smoking_history == "NON SMOKER" ~ "non smoker",
    TRUE ~ smoking_history   
  ))
